```

This proves that the opposite group `Gᵐᵒᵖ` is a diffeological group.

```tactics
variable (G)

/-- The map `(x, y) ↦ (x, x * y)` as a diffeomorphism. This is a shear mapping. -/
@[to_additive /-- The map `(x, y) ↦ (x, x + y)` as a homeomorphism. This is a shear mapping. -/]
protected def DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight : G × G ᵈ≃ G × G :=
  { Equiv.prodShear (Equiv.refl _) Equiv.mulLeft with
    dsmooth_toFun := dsmooth_fst.prod_mk dsmooth_mul
    dsmooth_invFun := dsmooth_fst.prod_mk <| dsmooth_fst.inv.mul dsmooth_snd }
```

This defines a diffeomorphism `DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight` from `G × G` to `G × G`. The map is `(x, y) ↦ (x, x * y)`. The proof involves showing that this map and its inverse are smooth.

```tactics
@[to_additive (attr := simp)]
theorem DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight_coe :
    ⇑(DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight G) = fun z : G × G ↦ (z.1, z.1 * z.2) :=
  rfl
```

This theorem states that the coercion of the diffeomorphism `DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight G` to a function is equal to the explicit map `(z.1, z.1 * z.2)`. This is true by definition.

```tactics
@[to_additive (attr := simp)]
theorem DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight_symm_coe :
    ⇑(DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight G).symm = fun z : G × G ↦ (z.1, z.1⁻¹ * z.2) :=
  rfl
```

This theorem states that the coercion of the inverse of the diffeomorphism `DDiffeomorph.shearMulRight G` is equal to the explicit map `(z.1, z.1⁻¹ * z.2)`. This is true by definition.

```tactics
variable {G}
```

This sets up the context for the next theorem.

```tactics
omit [DiffeologicalSpace H] [Group H] [DiffeologicalGroup H] in
/-- For any group homomorphism to a diffeological group, the induced diffeology makes the
domain a diffeological group too. -/
@[to_additive /-- For any group homomorphism to a diffeological group, the induced diffeology makes
  the domain a diffeological group too. -/]
protected theorem IsDInducing.diffeologicalGroup {F : Type*} [Group H] [DiffeologicalSpace H]
    [FunLike F H G] [MonoidHomClass F H G] (f : F) (hf : IsDInducing f) : DiffeologicalGroup H :=
  { toDSmoothMul := hf.dsmoothMul _
    toDSmoothInv := hf.dsmoothInv (map_inv f) }
```

This proves that if `f : F → G` is an isomorphism from a group `F` to a diffeological group `G`, then `F` can be given the structure of a diffeological group.

```tactics
omit [DiffeologicalSpace H] [Group H] [DiffeologicalGroup H] in
@[to_additive]
theorem diffeologicalGroup_induced {F : Type*} [Group H] [FunLike F H G] [MonoidHomClass F H G]
    (f : F) : @DiffeologicalGroup H (DiffeologicalSpace.induced f ‹_›) _ :=
  letI := DiffeologicalSpace.induced f ‹_›
  { toDSmoothMul := dsmoothMul_induced f
    toDSmoothInv := dsmoothInv_induced f (map_inv f) }
```

This establishes that the induced diffeology on the domain `F` via the map `f : F → G` (where `G` is a diffeological group) results in `F` being a diffeological group.

